abstract: The co-chair of South Carolina's caucus for African-American women endorsed billionaire U.S. presidential candidate Tom Steyer on Sunday, helpful backing in the first state to vote in which most Democrats are black.
snippet: The co-chair of South Carolina's caucus for African-American women endorsed billionaire U.S. presidential candidate Tom Steyer on Sunday, helpful backing in the first state to vote in which most Democrats are black.
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - The co-chair of South Carolina's caucus for African-American women endorsed billionaire U.S. presidential candidate Tom Steyer on Sunday, helpful backing in the first state to vote in which most Democrats are black.
headline_main: Black Democratic Group Co-Chair Endorses Steyer in South Carolina

abstract: An excerpt from “The Cactus League,” by Emily Nemens
snippet: An excerpt from “The Cactus League,” by Emily Nemens
lead_paragraph: Welcome to Salt River Fields, the newest spring training facility in Scottsdale, Arizona. Turn east off of Pima, drive down the fresh boulevard, Lions Way. You’re flanked by parking lots so new they still smell like tar, their white hatching wet: ample parking for the anticipated crowds, already sold out for opening day. Note the median’s plantings: environmentally sustainable xeriscape. Of course, this is 2011, and the club cares about our natural resources, is mindful of the perpetual drought in Phoenix metro. A few Christmas cacti bloom, despite it being February.
headline_main: ‘The Cactus League,’ by Emily Nemens: An Excerpt

abstract: On a wild stretch of Pacific shoreline, Costa Chica draws artists, architects, surfers, yogis and “naughty friends.”
snippet: On a wild stretch of Pacific shoreline, Costa Chica draws artists, architects, surfers, yogis and “naughty friends.”
lead_paragraph: Stepping off the plane in Puerto Escondido, on the Pacific Coast of Oaxaca, I gulped the thick, tropical air. After three days in Mexico’s high-elevation capital, inhaling the vital, pungent smell of sea and damp vegetation felt like a resuscitation.

abstract: A ground-level view of what has happened in the frenzied final days as voters gather to pick a winner.
snippet: A ground-level view of what has happened in the frenzied final days as voters gather to pick a winner.
lead_paragraph: KNOXVILLE, Iowa — In the week before the Iowa caucuses, the state becomes a crazy place. Everyone wants to know what’s going on, so they ask people like me. I’m a small-town Iowa radio guy on the wrong side of 60 in suspenders, Carhartts and mud boots.
